You can make use of the css pseudo element `::before` 

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-css --&gt;

    .img_container {
    	position: relative;
    	width: 500px;
    	height: 380px;
    	color: #333;
    	text-align: center;
    	padding-top: 20%;
    	font-size: 20px;
    }
    
    .img_container::before {
    	content: &quot; &quot;;
    	position: absolute;
    	left: 0;
    	top: 0;
    	width: 100%;
    	height: 100%;
    	box-sizing: border-box;
    	background-image: url(&quot;https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/a/a1/Mallard2.jpg&quot;);
    	background-size: contain;
    	background-repeat: no-repeat;
    	filter: blur(2px);
    	z-index: 0;
    }
    
    .img_text {
    	position: relative;
    }

&lt;!-- language: lang-html --&gt;

    &lt;div class=&quot;img_container&quot;&gt;
      &lt;div class=&quot;img_text&quot;&gt; I want to be clear! &lt;/div&gt;
    &lt;/div&gt;

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

`::before` with the `content: &quot; &quot;` creates a [pseudo element](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/CSS/Pseudo-elements) before the div with class .img_text (use your browser inspect tool to see the element). This is the element we style and add a background to. 

Note that you also have `::after` pseudo element to add at the end.

